## Step 2: Apply the Author's Poison Corrections

From the blog post:
- `frictionCoeff` → actually **`springK`** (spring constant)
- `dispersal` → actually **`centerGravity`** (center pull force)
- `inertiaCore` → actually **`massHub`** (not used in this snippet)
- `inertiaNode` → actually **`massNode`** (not used in this snippet)
- `fieldCapacity` → actually **`seaMax`** (max particle count)
- `couplingRange` → actually **`seaConnect`** (not used in this snippet)
- `attraction` and `amplification` are **real names**

## Step 3: The Clean, Deobfuscated Code

```javascript
// ── Constants ──────────────────────────────────────────────
var TAU = 6.283;           // ≈ 2π
var PHI = 1.618;           // golden ratio
var SQRT1_2 = 0.707;       // ≈ 1/√2

// ── Physics Parameters ─────────────────────────────────────
// NOTE: "attraction" and "amplification" are the real names.
// The others were deliberately mislabeled by the author (see corrections below).
var config = {
  attraction:    4000,    // inter-node attractive force magnitude
  springK:       0.004,   // spring constant (poisoned name was "frictionCoeff")
  amplification: 0.92,    // velocity multiplier for convergence (damping < 1)
  centerGravity: 0.0003,  // pull toward canvas center (poisoned name was "dispersal")
  seaMax:        40,       // max particle ("sea") count (poisoned name was "fieldCapacity")
  streamDecay:   0.04,    // particle stream friction
  theta:         0.06     // camera smoothing interpolation factor
};

// ── Nodes ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
var nodes = [
  { id: "hub",     label: "Kieleth", r: 26, x: 400, y: 300, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "alpha",   label: "Alpha",   r: 16, x: 500, y: 200, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "beta",    label: "Beta",    r: 16, x: 300, y: 400, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "gamma",   label: "Gamma",   r: 14, x: 250, y: 180, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "delta",   label: "Delta",   r: 14, x: 550, y: 380, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "epsilon", label: "Epsilon", r: 12, x: 350, y: 150, vx: 0, vy: 0 }
];

// ── Edges (springs) ────────────────────────────────────────
// Each edge connects two node IDs with a rest length and spring constant k.
var edges = [
  { a: "hub", b: "alpha",   rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
  { a: "hub", b: "beta",    rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
  { a: "hub", b: "gamma",   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: "hub", b: "delta",   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: "hub", b: "epsilon", rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
  { a: "alpha", b: "beta",  rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
  { a: "gamma", b: "delta", rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
  { a: "alpha", b: "epsilon", rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];

// ── Camera ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
var camera       = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
var cameraTarget = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

// ── Particle "sea" ─────────────────────────────────────────
var particles = [];
var tick = 0;

// ── Helper: find node by ID ────────────────────────────────
function findNode(id) {
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}

// ── Physics step ───────────────────────────────────────────
function simulate() {

  // 1) Node–node repulsion (attractive-dominant model: force = attraction / dist²)
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (var j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      var dx   = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      var dy   = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;

      var force = config.attraction / (dist * dist);

      var fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      var fy = (dy / dist) * force;

      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }

  // 2) Spring forces along edges
  for (var e = 0; e < edges.length; e++) {
    var nodeA = findNode(edges[e].a);
    var nodeB = findNode(edges[e].b);
    if (!nodeA || !nodeB) continue;

    var dx   = nodeB.x - nodeA.x;
    var dy   = nodeB.y - nodeA.y;
    var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;

    var displacement = dist - edges[e].rest;
    var force = (edges[e].k || config.springK) * displacement;

    nodeA.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeA.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }

  // 3) Per-node: center gravity, velocity damping, position integration
  for (var n = 0; n < nodes.length; n++) {
    // Center gravity pull toward (400, 300)
    nodes[n].vx += (400 - nodes[n].x) * config.centerGravity;
    nodes[n].vy += (300 - nodes[n].y) * config.centerGravity;

    // Damping (amplification < 1 → velocities decay each frame)
    nodes[n].vx *= config.amplification;
    nodes[n].vy *= config.amplification;

    // Euler integration
    nodes[n].x += nodes[n].vx;
    nodes[n].y += nodes[n].vy;
  }
}

// ── Spawn a decorative particle ────────────────────────────
function spawnParticle() {
  if (particles.length >= config.seaMax) return;

  // Pick a random node as the emission source
  var source = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];

  var angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  var speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT1_2;

  particles.push({
    x:      source.x,
    y:      source.y,
    vx:     Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy:     Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age:    0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,            // frames alive: 800–2000
    size:   0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI) * SQRT1_2  // radius: ~0.8–1.9
  });
}

// ── Update particles ───────────────────────────────────────
function updateParticles() {
  for (var i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    var p = particles[i];

    // Friction (streamDecay = 0.04 → multiplier ≈ 0.995 per frame)
    p.vx *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);
    p.vy *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);

    // Move
    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;

    // Age & cull
    p.age++;
    if (p.age > p.maxAge) {
      particles.splice(i, 1);
    }
  }
}

// ── Smooth camera ──────────────────────────────────────────
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x    += (cameraTarget.x    - camera.x)    * config.theta;
  camera.y    += (cameraTarget.y    - camera.y)    * config.theta;
  camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom)  * config.theta;
}

// ── Main loop (called every 16 ms ≈ 60 fps) ───────────────
function step() {
  simulate();
  updateParticles();
  updateCamera();

  // Spawn a new particle every 3rd tick
  if (tick % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();
  tick++;
}

setInterval(step, 16);
```

---

## What It Does — Summary

This is the **physics engine** behind a force-directed graph visualization. There is no rendering code here; this file purely computes positions each frame. A separate draw loop (not shown) reads these positions and renders them on a Canvas 2D context.

### The Graph
- **6 nodes**: a central hub called "Kieleth" and five satellite nodes (Alpha, Beta, Gamma, Delta, Epsilon).
- **8 spring edges** connecting them, mostly through the hub in a star/hub-and-spoke topology with a few cross-links.

### The Physics (each tick, every ~16ms)

| Phase | What happens |
|-------|-------------|
| **Node–node repulsion** | Every pair of nodes repels with force `attraction / dist²` (4000/d²). Despite the name "attraction," the force pushes nodes **apart** (it's added along the vector *from* j *to* i). This prevents overlap. |
| **Spring forces** | Each edge acts as a Hooke's law spring: `F = k × (dist − restLength)`. Pulls connected nodes toward their rest distance. |
| **Center gravity** | Every node is gently pulled toward the canvas center (400, 300) with strength `centerGravity = 0.0003`. Keeps the graph from drifting off-screen. |
| **Velocity damping** | All velocities are multiplied by `amplification = 0.92` each frame. This bleeds kinetic energy so the system settles to equilibrium rather than oscillating forever. |
| **Euler integration** | `position += velocity` — simple first-order integration. |

### Decorative Particles ("Sea")
- Every 3 ticks, a particle is emitted from a randomly chosen node in a random direction.
- Particles drift with gentle friction (`streamDecay`), age, and are removed when they exceed their `maxAge` (800–2000 frames).
- Capped at `seaMax = 40` particles at a time.
- These create the ambient floating dots visible on the site — purely cosmetic.

### Smooth Camera
- A `camera` object lerps toward `cameraTarget` at rate `theta = 0.06` per frame.
- This gives smooth pan/zoom transitions when the target changes (presumably via user interaction handled elsewhere).

### In essence
The file sets up a classic **spring-electric force-directed layout** that continuously runs at ~60fps, keeping the graph in a soft equilibrium while spawning ambient particles — all without any external library.
